'''Shiwa Inari Shrine''' (志和稲荷神社) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located on the western foothills of the Masuzawa settlement in [[Shiwa Town]], [[Shiwa District, Iwate|Shiwa District]], [[Iwate Prefecture]], on the left bank of the [[Takinakawa River]]. It is a former prefectural shrine and currently a Beppyo Shrine under the Association of Shinto Shrines.

Locally, it is sometimes considered one of the [[Inari shrine#Three Great Inari Shrines of Japan|Three Great Inari Shrines of Japan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lafrance.co.jp/company.htm |title=La France Onsen Kaisha|publisher=[[Shiwa Town]] [[Third Sector]] Shiwa Machizukuri Kikaku |accessdate=2018-11-16 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tsukinowa-iwate.com/press/index8p40.html |title=Featured Information on Meijo Kigan |publisher=[[Tsukinowa Sake Brewery]] |accessdate=2018-11-16 }}</ref> or one of the [[Inari shrine#Five Great Inari Shrines of Japan|Five Great Inari Shrines of Japan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iwatekeizai.org/watching/watching_201801/8066/ |title=Shiwa Inari Shrine in Shiwa Town |publisher=[[Iwate Bank]] Iwate Economic Research Institute |date=2018-01 |accessdate=2018-12-16 }}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=2018-12|title=Sources claiming Shiwa Inari Shrine as one of the Five Great Inari Shrines of Japan}}.

Nearby, there is another shrine called [[Shiwa Koinari Shrine]].

== Enshrined Deities ==
The enshrined deities are [[Ukanomitama|Ukanomitama no Okami]] (Inari Okami), [[Sarutahiko|Sarutahiko no Okami]], and [[Oomiyanome no Okami]]. The shrine considers Oomiyanome no Okami to be another name for [[Ame-no-Uzume|Ame-no-Uzume no Mikoto]].

During the [[Edo period]], the shrine also worshipped [[Juichimen Kannon]] as its principal Buddha.<ref>『Goryobun Shato』. This document, compiled in the mid-18th century, lists temples and shrines within the Morioka domain.</ref>

== History ==
According to tradition, the shrine was founded in [[Tenki]] 5 (1057) when [[Minamoto no Yoriyoshi]] enshrined a divided spirit from [[Fushimi Inari Taisha]] in Kyoto to pray for victory in his campaign against the Abe clan during the [[Former Nine Years' War]]. Later, the Fujiwara clan members who ruled Shiwa District, such as Hiramune Takanari, are said to have rebuilt the shrine.<ref name="Kadokawa">『Kadokawa Japan Place name Dictionary』.</ref> Another tradition claims that [[Minamoto no Yoritomo]] rebuilt the shrine during the [[1189|Oshu War]] in 1189.<ref name="Heibonsha">『Iwate Place names』.</ref> There is also a tradition stating that the shrine was founded during the [[Daido]] period (806-810), and another stating that [[Shiba Ienaga]] enshrined the deity from Fushimi Inari when he came to Shiwa District in [[Kenmu]] 2 (1335) as the commander of Oshu.<ref name="Heibonsha"/><ref>『Shinto Dictionary』 Vol. 2, Heibonsha, 1939.</ref>

The shrine received patronage from the Shiba clan, who ruled Shiwa District throughout the [[Muromachi period]]. In [[Tensho]] 16 (1588), [[Shiba Tsunenao]] built the shrine building,<ref>The shrine possesses a building plaque dated May 28, 1588.</ref> but after Tsunenao was ousted by [[Nanbu Nobunao]] that same year, the Nanbu clan became the shrine's patrons. After being attacked by Nobunao, Tsunenao hid in the shrine's affiliated temple, Joju-in, and then fled to Sanno-kai (a small basin in the upper reaches of the Takinakawa River, in present-day Tsuchidate, Shiwa Town).<ref name="Heibonsha"/>

The Nanbu clan's patronage continued, with records showing that Nanbu Nobunao donated over 24 koku of rice fields in [[Keicho]] 4 (1599). Additional donations were made, including 20 koku from Hirasawa Village (present-day Hirasawa, Shiwa Town) in 1612, and another 10 koku in 1614. In [[Shoo]] 1 (1652), Nanbu Nobuaki donated 7 koku of shrine land. By [[Kaei]] 2 (1849), the total donations from the Nanbu domain amounted to 70 koku.<ref name="Heibonsha"/> festivals and other events were frequently attended by representatives from the Nanbu clan, confirming the shrine's status as a place of worship for the Nanbu family.<ref name="Kadokawa"/> In [[Tenpo]] 5 (1834), Nanbu Toshiharu constructed a pilgrimage road from [[Morioka]] to the shrine, modeled after the [[Nikko Kaido]], a distance of about 15 km (5 ri).

The shrine was ranked as a [[Village Shrine]] in the early [[Meiji]] period and was elevated to a [[Prefectural Shrine]] in [[Taisho]] 7 (1918). After World War II, it joined the Association of Shinto Shrines and was designated as a Beppyo Shrine in [[Showa]] 32 (1957).

== Rituals ==
Until the early Meiji period, the shrine was influenced by the syncretism of Shinto and Buddhism and was managed by the Shugen-do temple Joju-in.

== Grounds ==
The shrine grounds feature a cedar tree over 1,000 years old, known as the "Inariyama Great Cedar," which is considered sacred. There is a custom of searching for white fox hair at the base of the cedar tree to pray for longevity.

